{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487182"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:00:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:00:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"273"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/273"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.07,0.03,0.02,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"273"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78938"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/273"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"273"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64287"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"11118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7310"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78938"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic enquiring about cervical cancer screening. She has had normal Pap smears in the past and a cervical screening test two years ago which was reported as low risk (HPV not detected). She believes that she is due for a repeat test. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no symptoms of abnormal vaginal bleeding, discharge, or pain during intercourse. Her menstrual periods have always been quite heavy, requiring 2-4 hourly tampon changes for 4-5 days. Her sexual debut was at 17 years of age and she completed the HPV vaccine course as a teenager. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding cervical screening?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Return for screening in three years","Continue two-yearly Pap smears until age 75","Report heavy menstrual periods at screening as this requires colposcopy","Early sexual debut requires immediate screening","Undergo routine HPV and cytology co-testing every three years"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the current Australian cervical screening program, which replaced Pap smears with HPV testing in December 2017. The program involves HPV testing with reflex liquid-based cytology only if HPV is detected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReturn for screening in three years\u003C/strong\u003E is correct as this patient had a negative HPV test two years ago. The screening interval is five years for women with a negative HPV result, so she has three years remaining until her next test is due.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue two-yearly Pap smears until age 75\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as Pap smears have been replaced by HPV testing. The new program involves five-yearly screening from ages 25-74 for women with low-risk results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReport heavy menstrual periods at screening as this requires colposcopy\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Heavy menstrual bleeding alone is not an indication for colposcopy. Colposcopy is indicated for HPV 16/18 positive results or abnormal cytology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEarly sexual debut requires immediate screening\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While sexual debut before age 14 is considered higher risk, this patient\u0027s sexual debut at age 17 does not place her in a higher risk category.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUndergo routine HPV and cytology co-testing every three years\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Co-testing is only indicated when women present with symptoms suspicious for cervical cancer such as post-coital bleeding or intermenstrual bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Australian cervical screening program involves HPV testing every five years from age 25-74 for women with low-risk results.","Women with a negative HPV test result should be screened again in five years.","Co-testing (HPV and cytology) is only indicated for women with symptoms of cervical cancer such as post-coital or intermenstrual bleeding."],"references":["National Cervical Screening Programme. In: Australian Government, Department of Health [online]. Cited 2020 Aug 23. Available at:\u00a0http://www.cancerscreening.gov.au/internet/screening/publishing.nsf/Content/cervical-screening-1."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64287"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"273"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64287"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T11:54:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T11:54:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"273"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78938"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rela